  "why": "The paper enforces semantic consistency and naturalness for each transformation (they define transformations to target a single perceptual property, implement local-projection to avoid changing unrelated regions, and validate consistency/uniqueness and the naturalness of mutated images via a large human study). However, the testing pipeline still accumulates mutants into the seed pool and applies further mutations to those mutants (Alg. 1), and the paper does not impose per-seed constraints that bound cumulative distortion relative to the original seed (no mechanism such as validating similarity to the original seed or fixing semantically critical content across all iterations is described). The authors do introduce an EP-oriented regulation that forces selection of fresh transformations (preventing being trapped on the same transformation), but this does not equate to preventing iterative drift from compounding small per-step changes relative to original seeds. Therefore the approach ensures plausibility/consistency at the single-transformation / successive-step level but does not account for cumulative distortion across many mutation iterations, matching the Metric's definition of \"Medium.\"",
  "evidence": "Sec. 2.1 (p.1607) Definition 1: \"An input transformation consistently targets one unique property (not targeted by other transformations) across different inputs.\"; Sec. 4.1 (p.1608) Eq.4 and description of local transformations: \"a local transformation can be achieved by first projecting v onto B before editing F: x' = G(z + B B^T v).\"; Sec. 5 (Pilot Study, p.1609): \"Correctness: ... the percentages of transformations satisfying the requirements are 0.94 and 0.95, respectively... Validity of Mutated Images. We do not observe invalid images (i.e., an image is 'unnatural' and hardly recognized by humans) generated by our transformations.\"; Alg. 1 (Testing pipeline for accumulation objectives, p.1611): shows mutants are added back to the seed pool: \"x'.prio <- 10; X.add(x')\", indicating further mutations may be applied to previously mutated inputs; Sec. 7.3 (p.1612): \"Solution. ... we always select transformations whose associated input properties have not been deemed erroneous... Once an EP has been detected, it will never be considered in further testing.\" — this regulation forces fresh transformations but does not enforce similarity to the original seed or otherwise prevent cumulative per-step distortion across multiple mutation rounds."
